Event and type of location required. In Brooklyn in 1876, almost 300 people died in one of these
events, whose victims were mostly from the upper family circle. Eddie Foy tried to calm the crowd during
one of these events at Chicago’s Iroquois in 1903, but over 600 people died, making it the deadliest of
these events in history. In the opinion to 1919’s Schenck v. United States, Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr.
wrote that “the most stringent protection of free speech would not protect” someone from falsely shouting
that one of these events was occurring. For the point, name this specific type of disaster, one of which
destroyed Shakespeare’s Globe after a cannon accident.=====
theater fire =====